<main>
  <h1>Architecture Deep-Dive</h1>
  <p>A walkthrough of every design decision in the platform, with the interview reasoning behind each choice.</p>

  <h2>1. LangGraph Graph Structure</h2>
  <p>The agent pipeline uses a <strong>hub-and-spoke</strong> topology. Every specialist agent (Planner, Coder, Reviewer, Tester) returns control to the Supervisor after completion. The Supervisor is the only routing node.</p>

  <pre>supervisor → planner → supervisor → coder → supervisor → reviewer
                                  ↑                          ↓
                            (revision loop)           supervisor → tester → END
                                  ↑_________score &lt; 0.7___________|</pre>

  <div class="callout">
    <strong>Interview point:</strong> Hub-and-spoke vs direct agent-to-agent edges.
    Direct edges create O(N²) routing complexity as you add agents — each agent
    must know about all possible next agents. Hub-and-spoke keeps routing logic
    in one place, making it testable and extensible.
  </div>

  <h3>Supervisor routing function</h3>
  <p>The supervisor is a <strong>pure function</strong> — no LLM call, no side effects. It reads the current <code>AgentState</code> and returns the next node name as a string. This makes it fully unit-testable with a plain dict input, and adds zero latency to the routing decision.</p>

  <h3>Loop guard</h3>
  <p><code>revision_count</code> in <code>AgentState</code> tracks how many Coder→Reviewer cycles have run. The supervisor checks it before routing back to the Coder. At <code>max_revision_cycles=3</code>, it accepts best-effort output and routes to Tester regardless of score.</p>

  <h2>2. SQS + ECS Async Pattern</h2>
  <p>The API returns <strong>202 Accepted</strong> immediately, decoupling HTTP lifetime from LLM execution time (30–120s). Clients poll <code>GET /run/{"{id}"}</code> until status changes.</p>

  <table>
    <thead><tr><th>Parameter</th><th>Value</th><th>Why</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>WaitTimeSeconds</td><td>20</td><td>Long-poll — avoids $0.40/M API calls from short-polling</td></tr>
      <tr><td>VisibilityTimeout</td><td>300s</td><td>Must exceed max graph runtime; enables at-least-once retry</td></tr>
      <tr><td>maxReceiveCount</td><td>3</td><td>Three processing attempts before routing to DLQ</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Delete-on-success</td><td>Only after execute()</td><td>Failed messages stay in queue for retry</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2>3. DynamoDB Single-Table Design</h2>
  <pre>Table: orchestrator-runs
PK (S): run_id   SK (S): sk = "RUN"

GSI: status-createdAt-index
  PK: status → enables "all running jobs" without scan
  SK: created_at → time-range sub-queries

TTL: auto-deletes items after 30 days</pre>

  <div class="callout">
    <strong>Interview point:</strong> The GSI on <code>status + created_at</code> enables the
    <code>GET /run?status=running</code> query without a full table scan.
    TTL eliminates the need for a separate cleanup job. Fixed SK="RUN" anticipates
    future sub-items (e.g. per-agent spans as SK="SPAN#planner").
  </div>

  <h2>4. OpenTelemetry + ADOT Sidecar</h2>
  <p>The application sends traces via OTLP/gRPC to <code>localhost:4317</code> — the ADOT sidecar container in the same ECS task. ADOT forwards to CloudWatch X-Ray. Swapping observability backends requires only an ADOT config change, not a code deployment.</p>

  <pre>Trace: run_abc123
├── span: http.post /run              [FastAPI middleware]
│
└── span: worker.execute run_abc123   [SQS consumer]
    ├── span: agent.planner
    │   └── span: llm.chat gpt-4o
    ├── span: agent.coder
    │   └── span: llm.chat gpt-4o
    ├── span: agent.reviewer
    │   └── span: llm.chat gpt-4o
    └── span: agent.tester
        └── span: llm.chat gpt-4o</pre>

  <h2>5. Retry + Fallback Decorator</h2>
  <p>The <code>@with_retry(max_attempts=3, fallback_attr="fallback_llm")</code> decorator applies to all agent <code>__call__</code> methods. On the last attempt, <code>self.llm</code> is temporarily swapped to <code>self.fallback_llm</code> (gpt-4o-mini).</p>

  <div class="callout">
    <strong>Key detail — jitter:</strong> The backoff delay is <code>base * 2^attempt + random(0,1)</code>.
    The <code>random(0,1)</code> term prevents thundering herd — without it, all workers
    that hit a rate limit simultaneously wake up at the same moment and re-hammer the API.
  </div>

  <h2>6. CloudWatch EMF Metrics</h2>
  <p>Custom metrics are emitted as Embedded Metric Format JSON log lines — no <code>PutMetricData</code> API calls. The CloudWatch agent parses them automatically. This means cost-per-run is a native CloudWatch metric, queryable in dashboards and alertable.</p>

  <h2>7. ECS Auto-scaling on Queue Depth</h2>
  <p>The Fargate service scales on <code>ApproximateNumberOfMessagesVisible</code>, not CPU utilization. CPU-based scaling is reactive — CPU spikes after the work has already been sitting in the queue. Queue-depth scaling is predictive — workers are added before latency increases.</p>

  <h2>8. CDK vs Terraform</h2>
  <p>AWS CDK (Python) was chosen over Terraform for three reasons: same language as application code (no context-switching), L3 constructs encode AWS best practices by default, and no S3 state file bootstrapping required.</p>
